2026-04-16 12:12:01 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Internal wiring between series diode output node and lamp nodes inside load module'] hypothesis_explanation='All elements in the load module test individually good: the main lamp filament measures 120 Ω, the indicator lamp 500 Ω, both match nominal; the input cables show low resistance continuity; and the series diode shows a correct 0.7 V forward drop when tested. Yet, when 12 V is applied to the external terminals in the correct polarity, there is 0 V at both terminals of the indicator lamp (and similarly no voltage across the main lamp) and no current flows in either lamp. This means the diode is not actually delivering the forward‑biased supply to the lamp node.\n\nGiven that the diode itself is functional, the only remaining fault consistent with 0 V at the lamps while the diode tests good is an open circuit in the internal conductor path between the diode’s output node and the common node feeding the two lamp terminals (or an equivalent misconnection so that the diode’s cathode is not connected to the lamp node at all). The continuity tests performed earlier did not explicitly verify the connection from the diode’s downstream terminal to the lamp node; they only checked terminal‑to‑terminal continuity and lamp filament integrity. Therefore the root cause is most likely an internal open or miswired link between the series diode output and the lamp/indicator node inside the load module, so that the lamps are never actually connected to the diode’s output and thus never receive voltage, despite all other components being healthy.'
